:["English: from the Middle English and Older Scots personal name   Gibb   (a pet form of <i>Gilbert</i>) + <i>son</i>, hence ‘son of <i>Gibb</i>’. The name is very common in Ireland, having arrived in that country in the 17th century. It is also occasionally adopted for <i>Ó Gibealláin</i>, see   Giblin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gibb","meanings":["English: from the personal name <i>Gibb</i>, a pet form of <i>Gilbert</i> (compare   Gibbs  ). This surname is also frequent in Scotland."]}]},{"name":"Timothy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form, used in the Authorized Version of the Bible (alongside the Latin form <i>Timotheus</i>), of the Greek name <i>Timotheos</i>, from <i>timē</i> ‘honour’ + <i>theos</i> ‘god’. This was the name of a companion of  St Paul;  according to tradition, he was stoned to death for denouncing the worship of  Diana . It was not used in England before the Reformation but has been in steady use since the 18th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Major","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the personal name <i>Malg(i)er</i>, <i>Maug(i)er</i>, an Old French form of ancient Germanic <i>Madalgar(i)</i> (see   Mauger  ).","Hungarian: from a shortened form of <i>majorosgazda</i> (see   Majoros  ) or a derivative of German   Meyer  .","Polish, Czech, and Slovak: from the military rank <i>major</i> (derived from Latin <i>maior</i> ‘greater’), a word related to English <i>mayor</i> and the German surname   Meyer  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mauger","meanings":["French and Channel Islands (Guernsey and Jersey): from the Old French (Norman) personal name <i>Maug(i)er</i>, <i>Malg(i)er</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Madalgar(i)</i>, <i>Malger</i>, composed of the elements <i>madal</i> ‘council, meeting’ and <i>gar(i)</i> ‘spear’, or from <i>Amalgar(i)</i>, with the first element <i>amal</i> ‘capable, brave, eager’. Compare   Major  ,   Monger  , and   Munger  .","Probably also an altered form of German   Mager  ."]},{"name":"Maslin","meanings":["English (mainly Wiltshire and Gloucestershire): from the Old French and Middle English personal names <i>Mazelin</i> (male) or <i>Mazeline</i> (female), which are double diminutives of ancient Germanic <i>Mazo</i>, <i>Matso</i> (male) and <i>Maza</i>, <i>Matsa</i> (female). These are probably pet forms of ancient Germanic names such as <i>Mathalgar</i> (see   Major  ), which have <i>mathal-</i> ‘speech’ as their first element, but the female name might also be a pet form of <i>Matild(a)</i> (see   Tillett  )."]},{"name":"Moger","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."]},{"name":"Majors","meanings":["English: variant of   Major  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Mager","meanings":["Dutch and German: nickname for a thin man, Middle Dutch, Middle High German <i>mager</i> ‘thin’. This surname is also found in Poland and Czechia and possibly also in Slovakia (see 3 below).","English (Lincolnshire and Middlesex): variant of   Major  .","Romanian and Slovak: variant of   Magyar   ‘Hungarian’. Slovak name may also be of German origin (see 1 above) or, in some cases, a habitational name from a placename Malý Mager (Kis-Magyar in Hungarian) in Bratislava County."]},{"name":"Majure","meanings":["Irish (northern): variant of   Major  .","History: According to family tradition John Majure came to North America from Ireland on the ship <i>Earl of Hillsborough</i> in 1767."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":61,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":70,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":81,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Timothy Major Gibson was born about 1488, in England. He had at least 1 son with Karen Faith Dolberry."},"et":{"about 1488–":"umbes 1488–Surnud","1488–Female":"1488–Surnud","1505–1577":"1505–1577","1488–Male":"1488–Surnud","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1577":"1577","1488":"1488","about 1488":"umbes 1488","       1505":"1505","1549":"1549","1505":"1505",", Bedford, England":"Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1488–":"noin 1488–Kuollut","1488–Female":"1488–Kuollut","1505–1577":"1505–1577","1488–Male":"1488–Kuollut","1569":"1